00:34:05,541 --> 00:34:11,927
core of the end of the Arthurian narrative as well. Arthur is this noble just king who is

538
00:34:12,827 --> 00:34:17,992
thrown off the throne by his son who's just rubbish, who's just this power-hungry brat

539
00:34:19,153 --> 00:34:22,837
who doesn't want anything apart from just to hurt his dad and to screw stuff up.

540
00:34:24,895 --> 00:34:29,218
and Arthur goes to face him even though he knows he can't win against this, he can't,

541
00:34:29,258 --> 00:34:33,861
he doesn't have a chance but he has to, and that's always spoke to me as a kind of,

542
00:34:34,121 --> 00:34:37,963
you know, as an honourable and noble sacrifice in that kind of romantic vision.

543
00:34:38,946 --> 00:34:41,667
The book that I liked as a kid, which is called The Once and Future King, was written

544
00:34:42,367 --> 00:34:48,471
very much about the rise of Nazism in the 30s, but as a King Arthur story, but that it's that same tone and that

545
00:34:48,531 --> 00:34:50,432
same tone applies now and that sense of

546
00:34:50,992 --> 00:34:53,134
we can be good people and we should be good people.

547
00:34:54,975 --> 00:35:00,037
And what do you do when the people in charge and the people who have all of the power

